You provide the executor from the outside then `verify`.

```
class MyClass {
  private final ScheduledThreadPoolExecutor stp;
  public MyClass(ScheduledThreadPoolExecutor ex) { stp = ex; }

  public void start() {
    stp.scheduleAtFixedRate(executeRunnable(), 2,2, TimeUnit.SECONDS); 
  }
}

class MyTest {
  @Mock
  ScheduledThreadPoolExecutor exec;

  public void testStart() {
    MyClass sut = new MyClass(exec);
    sut.start();
    verify(exec).scheduleAtFixedRate(any(), eq(2), eq(2), eq(TimeUnit.SECONDS));
  }
}
```

This way you make sure the class schedules a runnable at the expected time. If you want to ensure the behavior of the runnable, you can use an `ArgumentCaptor`, but I don&#39;t see how you would verify a `System.out.println()`.

